function minSkips(dist, speed, hoursBefore) {
    const n = dist.length;
    const dp = Array.from({ length: n + 1 }, () => Array(n + 1).fill(1e6));

    dp[0][0] = 0;
    for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        dp[i][0] = Math.ceil(dp[i - 1][0] + dist[i - 1] / speed) - 1;
    }

    for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        for (let skip = 1; skip <= i; skip++) {
            dp[i][skip] = Math.min(dp[i][skip], dp[i - 1][skip - 1] + dist[i - 1] / speed);
            dp[i][skip] = Math.min(dp[i][skip], Math.ceil(dp[i - 1][skip] + dist[i - 1] / speed));
        }
    }

    for (let skip = 0; skip <= n; skip++) {
        if (dp[n][skip] <= hoursBefore) {
            return skip;
        }
    }
    return -1;
}
```

    The algorithm uses dynamic programming to determine the minimum number of skips required to arrive at the meeting on time. We create a DP table `dp` with dimensions `(n+1) x (n+1)`, where `dp[i][j]` represents the time taken to travel `i` roads with `j` skips. The cell with `dp[n][skip]` represents the time taken to reach the meeting after traveling all `n` roads with `skip` skips.

First, we initialize the DP table. For each `i`, we set `dp[i][0]` as the time taken to travel `i` roads without any skips (i.e. waiting the full hour after each road).

Next, we loop through each road and for each number of skips from 1 to the road index. We calculate the minimum time of two cases: skipping the rest after the previous road and not skipping it. If we skip the rest, we simply add the time for the current road. If we don't skip it, we use `ceil` to round up to the nearest integer hour and then add the time for the current road. We then update the DP table with the minimum time for both cases.

Finally, we loop through the DP table row representing the last road (`dp[n][skip]`), and if we find a time less than or equal to `hoursBefore`, we return the number of skips. If we don't find any suitable time, we return -1, indicating that it's impossible to arrive on time.

